# AI Hub - rules for AI sections

This rule extends [sections.mdc](sections.mdc). Read it first.

The shared services in `src/services/` are the **only** place where vendor
SDKs (OpenAI, Anthropic, keyring, httpx, pypdf, …) live. Sections own
their prompts and pipelines so we never touch a shared "prompts" file.

## Per-section AI files

Inside `src/sections/<key>/` you may add (all optional except as noted):

- `prompts.py` — system prompts, including a re-statement of the
  no-hallucination clause and any domain rules. Build user messages as
  `build_*_user(...)` helpers.
- `schema.py` — JSON Schema dicts used by structured-output calls.
- `pipeline.py` — orchestration. One public function per logical step
  (`extract_*`, `analyze_*`, `generate_*`, `refine_*`). Each step calls
  `src.services.ai_provider.run(...)`.
- `state.py` — module-level singleton `STATE = SectionState()` for
  values that must survive theme / language / tab rebuilds.
- `refs.py` — cross-tab rerender hooks (optional, but useful for tabbed
  sections).
- `tab_*.py` — one file per visible tab (Setup / Match / Documents / …)
  to keep the view file small.
- `how_to.py` — wires `src.components.how_to_dialog.open_how_to(...)`
  to the section copy. Header `?` button opens it.

## Hard rules — never break these

- **No direct vendor imports.** Sections must not `import openai` or
  `import anthropic`. The single entry point is
  `src.services.ai_provider.run(system, user, schema=…, ...)`.
  `ai_provider` already prepends a no-hallucination policy clause; do
  not strip it.
- **Per-section system prompts must repeat the domain rules.** They do
  not have to repeat the global no-hallucination rule (the provider does
  it for them) but every domain rule the user listed for that section
  must live in `prompts.py` and be referenced by every doc-level prompt.
- **API keys belong in the OS keystore.** Use
  `src.services.secrets.{get,set,delete,has}_secret`. Never read keys
  from environment variables, never commit `.env` files, never log a
  key.
- **Cost-aware pipelines.** Cache structured outputs in section state
  (`STATE.candidate`, `STATE.job_spec`, `STATE.match`) and pass JSONs to
  follow-up doc generators instead of re-sending raw input text.
- **Demo mode is mandatory** for any section that calls a paid provider.
  Every pipeline function must short-circuit when `STATE.demo_mode` is
  `True` and return curated mock data — that lets users showcase the
  feature without spending tokens.
- **Runs persist on disk.** Use
 `src.services.store.new_run_dir(role, company, section=<section_key>)`
 and write outputs through `src.services.exporter.export_*`. The
 `section=` kwarg is mandatory - it routes the run into
 `outputs/<section_key>/<run-slug>-<timestamp>/` so the user can
 browse runs by section instead of one giant flat list. See
 [outputs-layout.mdc](outputs-layout.mdc) for the full convention
 + the "Open outputs folder" pattern. The history index lives at
 `~/AI Hub/history.json`. Every "Save complete analysis" call must
 request a fresh `new_run_dir(...)` - never reuse the previous run
 folder, otherwise two saves silently overwrite each other (see
 `ai_cv.pipeline.save_full_analysis`).
- **Pipeline functions log start / end / errors** through
 `src.services.logger.log_event` and `log_exception`. AI calls must
 emit a `*_start` line (with `kind`, `output_lang`, `demo_mode`) and a
 matching `*_done` or `*_failed` line (with `chars=` for sizes, never
 the raw text). This is what makes silent provider errors visible in
 **Settings -> Debug logs**. See `src/sections/ai_cv/pipeline.py`
 (`generate_document`, `refine_document`, `send_chat_message`,
 `save_full_analysis`) for the canonical pattern. The companion rule
 [sections.mdc](sections.mdc) has the full list of mandatory log
 events.

## Section file shape (AI-aware)

```python
# src/sections/<key>/section.py
from src.qt.icons import Icons
from src.sections._base import Section
from src.sections.<key>.context import build_context  # optional
from src.sections.<key>.strings import STRINGS
from src.sections.<key>.view import build_view

SECTION = Section(
    key="<key>",
    icon=Icons.<SOMETHING>_OUTLINED,
    labels={lang: STRINGS[lang]["nav_label"] for lang in STRINGS},
    build_view=build_view,
    build_context=build_context,
    order=<int>,
    nav_group="primary",  # or "secondary" for tools / settings
)
```

`pipeline.py` should look like:

```python
from src.services import ai_provider
from src.services import logger as logger_service
from src.sections.<key> import prompts, schema
from src.sections.<key>.state import STATE


def extract_thing(*, output_lang: str):
    logger_service.log_event(
        "INFO", "<key>.pipeline", "extract_thing_start",
        output_lang=output_lang, demo_mode=STATE.demo_mode,
    )
    if STATE.demo_mode:
        STATE.thing = ...  # mock
        logger_service.log_event(
            "INFO", "<key>.pipeline", "extract_thing_demo_done"
        )
        return
    try:
        result = ai_provider.run(
            system=prompts.THING_SYSTEM,
            user=prompts.build_thing_user(output_lang=output_lang, ...),
            schema=schema.THING_SCHEMA,
            schema_name="thing",
        )
    except ai_provider.ProviderError as exc:
        logger_service.log_exception(
            "<key>.pipeline", "extract_thing_provider_error", exc,
        )
        raise
    STATE.thing = result.data
    logger_service.log_event(
        "INFO", "<key>.pipeline", "extract_thing_done",
        fields=len(result.data or {}),
    )
```

That keeps every section's AI footprint in five files (prompts, schema,
state, pipeline, plus tabs) and a single shared dependency on
`src.services.ai_provider` (plus the shared `logger_service`).
